udes. The treatment of rape and ravishment is considered across a wide range of literary genres: hagiography, where female saints are repeatedly threatened with rape; legendary history, as in the stories of Lucretia and Helen; and romance, where acts of rape and ravishment challenge and shape chivalric order, and romance heroes are conceived through rape. Finally, the ways in which Malory and Chaucer write and rewrite rape and ravishment are examined.Dr CORINNE SAUNDERS is Lecturer in Medieval Studies, Department of English, University of Durham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian women saintsxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aHagiography. 0aRape in literature. 0aRapexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRomances, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aSex crimes in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomenxCrimes againstxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChaucer.  aCultural tradition.  aLiterature.  aMalory.  aMedieval England.  aRape.  aRavishment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615013540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846150135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846150135/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles